\section{Discussion}

\subsection{Species limits in the \textit{``Holothuria impatiens''} complex}

Species delineation is a complex issue and results can depend on the characters
and methods chosen. Here, using complementary approaches, combining discovery
(GMYC) and testing methods (*BEAST), we unraveled at least 13 species within the
complex ``\textit{Holothuria impatiens}'' supported by multiple lines of
evidence.

Traditional detailed taxonomic investigation in this complex failed to capture
the diversity unraveled by molecular analysis in this complex. For most putative
species thus identified, variation in traits not typically considered to
discriminate closely related species in sea cucumbers arose as being being
diagnostic in the light of genetic data. The consideration of geography and
differences in color patterns allowed the recognition of 10 species in the
complex in retrospect (Figure~\ref{fig:species-limits}). Taxonomic studies off
most marine invertebrates have relied on preserved specimens. Preservation can
render delicate morphological characters, including coloration, difficult or
impossible to see, as color patterns are frequently lost or fade with
time. Because hard parts are easily preserved, are often divergent among related
species, and their form is generally not impacted by preservation, they tend to
be favored for differentiating species. In sea cucumbers, species-level taxonomy
has relied almost entirely on the shape of ossicles, microscopic calcareous
secretions found in many tissues, because ossicles show substantial diversity
and variability, whilst variation in the simple anatomy of these animals is
limited at lower taxonomic levels. Even with ossicles, workers have mostly
focused on those found in the body wall, ignoring ossicles in internal
structures, until recent decades. Little attention has been given to
intraspecific variation, often ossicle assemblages are described from only a
single individual. This, in combination with the fact that related species often
co-occur in the same habitat, has contributed to the failure to recognize and
differentiate species in this complex.

Mitochondrial data has rapidly shown that several species are currently lumped
under \textit{Holothuria impatiens}, but the exact number of species and their
boundaries are more complex issues, in particular in groups which little about
their biology is known. The discovery methods, based on genetic differentiation
in COI, delineated at least 13 putative species. Ten of these were supported by
morphological (color) or broad geographical evidence, while three were not so
distinguishable.  Testing methods supported the remaining three as
genetically-isolated, cryptic species, corroborating the existence of at least
13 species. This study includes additional putative species whose status could
not be fully evaluated given that they were represented by a single individual
(see below).


\subsection{Species limits with GMYC}

Despite being widely used to delineate species, the sensitivity of the GMYC
method to factors affecting the shape of the tree used have not been
investigated thoroughly. Tree shape can be affected by biological factors or by
the type of analysis used to build the tree. Simulated data have been used to
test the influence of diversification rates, effective population sizes, and
migration rates, on the accuracy and precision of GMYC estimates
\citep{Papadopoulou2008, Esselstyn2012}. Some of the effects of the
methodological choices have been evaluated \citep{Pons2006, Monaghan2009,
  Fujisawa2013, Talavera2013}, but it is difficult to generalize as impacts
depend in part on the nature of the dataset.

The single-threshold method (sGMYC) provided more accurate estimates of the
number of species included in our sample compared to the multiple-threshold
method (mGMYC). Species delineated using sGMYC were corroborated by the
integrative taxonomic and multigene coalescent methods. In contrast, mGMYC
oversplit lineages supported by other lines of evidence. The lower accuracy of
mGMYC was also observed by the authors of the method using simulated datasets
\citep{Fujisawa2013}. In their study, they observed that the 95\% confidence set
for the estimated number of putative species using sGMYC and mGMYC overlapped
\citep{Fujisawa2013}. In this study, overlap between the estimates of sGMYC and
mGMYC was only observed when the analysis was performed on haplotypes but not
when it was performed on all sequences.

Performing the analysis on all sequences yielded to more accurate estimates of
the number of putative species, and made the method more robust to the choice of
priors. The number of putative species obtained using sGMYC with all sequences
was consistently 16, except for the relaxed clock with the Yule prior where it
was 14. The 16 species delineation was the most realistic as it recovers all
morphologically distinct ESUs. \citet{Talavera2013} found that using all
haplotypes or only unique haplotypes did not impact the number of species
estimated using GMYC. In contrast, we confirmed the theoretical expectation that
removing the duplicated sequences led to an overestimation of the number of
species and decreased the precision of the estimates if the tree was estimated
with BEAST. Removing identical sequences in the analysis overestimates the
effective population size parameters that BEAST uses. In turn, these
overestimated population sizes spuriously increase the time to coalescence for
the lineages, making the estimation of the inflection point between species- and
population-level coalescent events earlier in the tree, and more difficult to
detect. This bias leads to oversplitting and decreases accuracy. Investigating
how the number of individuals sampled per species increases the accuracy of the
delineation be worth investigating.
