% the differences in results


The results of this study highlights that the most appropriate combination of
priors and parameters to use in GMYC analyses depends on the
dataset. \citet{Monaghan2009} obtained the most accurate results when using a
coalescent prior and a relaxed log-normal clock on unique haplotypes (but they
did not perform the analysis using all sequences), and concluded that the Yule
prior led to an overestimation of the number of species for 4 of the 5 taxonomic
groups they investigated. On the other hand, \citet{Talavera2013} did not find
any notable differences in the number of species estimated using trees estimated
with different sets of priors. With this dataset, we obtained the most accurate
results when we used sGMYC on all sequences, and the best precision when using a
relaxed log-normal clock and a coalescent prior with exponential population
growth. The most appropriate set of parameters to use when performing a GMYC
analysis will be influenced by the number of individuals included, how divergent
the species are, and how heterogeneous the substitution rate is among the
species included. The species to be delineated also need to be reciprocally
monophyletic to make the GMYC approach suitable.

GMYC was developed with the intent of automating the estimation of the number of
species from large-scale single-locus sampling efforts, particularly from
environmental samples. In this context, a reasonable amount of inaccuracy or
imprecision from the true number of species may be acceptable. The advantage of
the method, namely providing a rapid and objective assessment of the number of
species, outweighs the possible deviations from the true value. However, in the
context of a taxonomic study where the goal is to identify species limits among
a few hundred individuals, factors affecting tree shape need to be considered,
and additional lines of evidence need to be included to validate the putative
species delineated \citep{Marshall2011a, Esselstyn2012}. More generally, any
study that uses GMYC to estimate species boundaries among a diverse group of
samples should run the analysis using several methods that produce robust
branch-length estimates.

